The paper deals with learning causal models from pairwise marginal independencies, which is a common problem in artificial intelligence and machine learning (cs.AI). The algorithms developed in the paper involve optimization and search techniques, which are also common in machine learning (cs.LG). The problem of characterizing DAGs that explain a given set of independencies is related to the field of discrete mathematics (cs.DM). The paper also discusses the use of information theory to quantify the amount of information conveyed by pairwise marginal independencies, which falls under the category of information theory (cs.IT). Finally, the paper's focus on causal inference and modeling makes it relevant to the subfield of social and information networks (cs.SI).
